<p>Two different questions get called "the cost of immigration" and they need separating
before any figure means anything.</p>

<ul class="panels">
  <li class="panel">
    <h2>What the system spends</h2>
    <p>Audited, published, and reasonably firm. That is this page.</p>
  </li>
  <li class="panel">
    <h2>What migration is worth fiscally</h2>
    <p>Contested, method-dependent, and lands within about plus or minus 1% of GDP either
    way. Not this page, see
    <a href="/common-claims/immigrants-pay-far-more-than-they-cost/">the claim check</a>.</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<p>A spending total tells you what a system costs to run. It tells you nothing about the net
fiscal position of migrants generally, and it is not evidence for or against that question.
The two get conflated constantly, in both directions.</p>

<h2>The total</h2>

<p>The National Audit Office puts government spending on the asylum system at
<strong>£{% figure "fiscal/government-spending-on-the-asylum-system" %} billion</strong> in
financial year 2024-25, covering the Home Office and the Ministry of Justice.</p>

<p>The NAO is explicit that this <strong>does not capture all costs</strong>, particularly
those falling on local authorities. It is a floor, not a ceiling.</p>

<h3>Where it goes</h3>

<p>These figures are <strong>nested, not parallel</strong>. Hotel spending sits inside
accommodation spending, which sits inside the total. Setting them side by side as though
they were separate items would double-count.</p>

