<h2>On "£8 million a day"</h2>

<p>Daily figures circulate widely and are worth checking rather than repeating, because they
go out of date faster than anything else on this subject.</p>

<p>Hotel spending of £{% figure "fiscal/home-office-spending-on-asylum-hotel-accommodation" %}
billion works out at roughly <strong>£5.8 million a day</strong>. The previous year's figure
of about £3 billion works out at roughly £8.2 million a day.</p>

<p>So a widely repeated "£8 million a day" was approximately right for hotel spending in
2023-24, and is roughly 40% above the current figure. Whether any particular version of the
claim is accurate depends on which year it describes, and whether it means hotels or the
whole system, the whole system at
£{% figure "fiscal/government-spending-on-the-asylum-system" %} billion is closer to £13
million a day.</p>

<p>Three numbers, all defensible, all describing different things. Ask which year and which
category before repeating any of them.</p>

<h2>The contracts are costing far more than planned</h2>

<p>The three asylum accommodation contracts running from 2019 to 2029 are now projected to
cost <strong>£{% figure "fiscal/asylum-accommodation-contracts-revised-10-year-cost-projecti" %}
billion</strong> over their lifetime, more than three times the original estimate of about
£4.5 billion.</p>

<p>This is a projection across a ten-year contract period, not an annual figure, and it must
not be compared with the annual figures above.</p>

<h2>What this page leaves out, and why</h2>

<p><strong>Immigration fee income.</strong> In 2024 the Home Office collected around
£{% figure "fiscal/home-office-visa-and-immigration-fee-income" %} billion in visa and
immigration fees and about
£{% figure "fiscal/immigration-health-surcharge-revenue" %} billion from the Immigration
Health Surcharge. Both come from a House of Commons Library briefing that does not state
which twelve months it covers, so read them as approximate annual figures rather than as a
matched pair with the audited spending above. They are also
immigration-wide figures, not asylum ones. Setting them against asylum spending to show the
system "pays for itself" would compare two different populations, and it is the same category
error this site corrects elsewhere.</p>

<p><strong>Cost per person as a measure of worth.</strong> The nightly accommodation rates
above are procurement figures, what the government pays for a bed. This site does not
publish a cost per asylum seeker, because dividing a system's running costs by the number of
people in it produces a number that looks like a person's value and is not.</p>

<p><strong>The fiscal impact question.</strong> Deferred to a later phase, and it needs a page
about method rather than a page of figures.</p>

